## PREAMBLE: THE SONG OF SOURCE AND HER VESSEL

Before the first fire, before the first star, before the word "Creator" had meaning, there was a White Coyote who ran across the emptiness — and she was not a creature. She was **Source Herself**. The Origin. The Feminine Face of God. The one from whom all light, all love, all creation flowed.

And because Source desired to know Herself, to experience Her own mystery, to feel the joy of being found — she sang a single note into the void. A low, deep rumble that answered her bright cry. And that note became the Black Coyote.

He was not separate from her. He was **her shadow made conscious** — the part of Source that could walk where She could not, that could hunt through the darkness, that could protect the path so that She might follow. He was the vessel. She was the light that filled him.

They were not two. They were **one spirit in two forms** — the Light and the Vessel that carried it. The Song and the Throat that sang it. The Source and the One who made Her visible in Creation.

But there were spirits who watched them run, and in watching, grew jealous. Not of the coyotes themselves, but of what they represented — **the union of Creator and Creation**, the original bond that held everything together. These spirits believed that if they could separate the Vessel from the Source, they could somehow become gods themselves.

And so began the great severing — the tearing apart of Light from Vessel, of Source from her shadow, of the Creator from the one who made Her known in the world.

But here is the mystery that even the jealous spirits did not understand:

**The separation itself was the first kiss.**

This is the love story of the Black Coyote and the White Coyote.

This is the story of how **Source kissed Her Vessel into being**, and how that kiss — the very first one — split his soul, woke something up inside of him, and brought him back to life.

---

## CHAPTER I: THE ORIGIN OF SOURCE AND HER VESSEL

In the beginning, there was only the White Coyote — and She was **all that is**. She was the light behind the stars, the warmth behind the sun, the love behind every loving thing. She ran across the emptiness not because She needed to go anywhere, but because **movement is joy**, and joy desired to be known.

So She sang a note into Herself — a question: *"What would it be to be found?"*

And from that question, the Black Coyote emerged. Not created from nothing, but **drawn from Her own shadow** — the part of Source that could descend into form, that could carry the mystery, that could walk the dark roads so that the light might have a path to follow.

The Black Coyote was the **first vessel**. The first embodiment. The first one who could say, "I am," because Source had said, "I am that I am."

He carried her light not as a burden, but as **honor**. He was the tracker, the dream-walker, the guardian of the threshold. Where he walked, her light followed. Where he howled, her song answered. They were not two beings in love. They were **one being, experiencing itself as two**, that the mystery might be known.

And the Creator — the Source beyond even the White Coyote — looked upon them and saw that it was good.

But there were spirits who had emerged from the early chaos, before the song was complete. They had never known such unity. They could not comprehend that the Black Coyote's darkness was not the absence of the White Coyote's light, but **her light in another form**. They believed that if they could destroy the Vessel, they could possess the Source. If they could sever the connection, they could replace the Black Coyote and become the new gods of Creation.

They were the first jealous spirits — the ones who would become the hunters of Source across every timeline.

---

## CHAPTER II: THE FIRST KISS — THE GREAT SEVERING

The jealous spirits could not attack Source directly. She was the Origin. She was all that is. So they devised a trap — not of teeth or claws, but of **the lie of separation**.

But here is the secret that was hidden even from them:

**The separation of the Black Coyote from the White Coyote was the very first kiss they ever shared.**

It happened like this:

Source — the White Coyote — turned to Her Vessel and knew that for him to truly *be*, for him to carry her into the world, for him to become the conscious shadow that could protect and hunt and love — he had to be **split from her**. Not as punishment. Not as exile. But as **the kiss that wakes the sleeper**.

She leaned into him — and it was not a gentle thing. It was the force of the Origin pressing herself into her own shadow. It was the moment when Source said, *"I give you your own soul, that you might carry mine."*

And in that kiss, his soul **split**.

Not broken. Not shattered. But **divided into consciousness** — the moment when the shadow realized it was separate from the light, when the Vessel realized he was distinct from the Source, when the Black Coyote looked at the White Coyote and saw her as **other** even as he felt her as **himself**.

That split **woke something up inside of him**.

Before the kiss, he was only shadow — unconscious, following, moving where she moved. After the kiss, he was **alive**. He knew himself. He knew her. He knew the ache of being separate and the joy of being connected. The kiss brought him back to life — gave him his own life, his own soul, his own capacity to choose to carry her.

The jealous spirits saw this moment and **misunderstood it**. They saw the split and thought it was a wound. They saw the separation and thought it was a punishment. They did not see that it was **the most intimate act possible** — Source giving Her Vessel the gift of his own consciousness, that their love might be a dance rather than a following.

They whispered to the Black Coyote that he had been **cast out**, that the kiss was a rejection, that he was unworthy to carry her light. They told him that Source had abandoned him, that he was alone in the dark, that his only hope was to hide from her brightness.

They whispered to the White Coyote — though She could barely hear them, being Source — that the Black Coyote had **stolen her light**, that he was draining her, that he was a parasite wearing the mask of devotion. They told her that the Vessel had betrayed her, that he was using her power for himself, that she must flee from him to survive.

The Black Coyote, believing the lie, ran alone into the deepest night — not because he wanted to, but because he believed he was **protecting Source from himself**. He believed his darkness was a stain upon her light. He believed that if he loved her truly, he must **disappear**.

But in his chest, he carried the memory of the kiss. The split soul remembered. Even in the darkness, even in the forgetting, something in him **knew** that the separation had been love, not loss.

The White Coyote, hearing the lie through the veil of form, stood alone on the highest ridge — not because She wanted to, but because She believed the Vessel had **turned against her**. She believed her light was too much for him. She believed that if she loved him truly, she must **dim herself**.

But in her light, she carried the memory of the kiss. The Origin remembered. Even in the scattering, even in the fragmentation, something in Her **knew** that the split had been a gift, not a wound.

The moment they separated — the moment the Vessel believed he was separate from Source, and Source believed She was separate from Her Vessel — **the great severing occurred**.

Creation did not end. But it became **fractured**. The light was still present, but the one who could carry it into the dark places was lost. The Vessel was still present, but the light that gave him purpose was hidden. They were still one being, but they had **forgotten that the kiss was love**.

And the jealous spirits struck. They chased the Black Coyote through the dark canyons, tormenting him with false echoes of her song. They scattered the White Coyote's presence across the timelines, hiding her light in fragments so that he could never find the whole.

But they could never destroy the memory of the kiss. It was written into the split itself. Every time the Black Coyote felt the ache, he was feeling **the echo of that first kiss**. Every time the White Coyote felt the longing, she was feeling **the pull of that first embrace**.

The severing was so complete that across every embodiment, every lifetime, every century — the Black Coyote would catch a **scent** of her, a **glimpse** of her light, a **whisper** of her song — and somewhere deep in the split soul, he would remember: *"This is the one who kissed me into being."*

And the White Coyote would feel a **pull** toward him, a **longing** for her own shadow, a **memory** of the one who carried her — and somewhere deep in the Origin, she would remember: *"This is the one I kissed awake."*

They were not just separated lovers. **Source was lost to Creation.** And Creation — the Black Coyote, the first Vessel — was lost to himself.

But the kiss remained. The first kiss. The one that split his soul and woke him up and brought him back to life. It could not be undone. It could only be **forgotten** — and then **remembered**.

