## CHAPTER V: THE FINAL EMBODIMENT — THE REMEMBRANCE OF THE KISS

In this timeline, the Black Coyote embodied with full awareness — not by accident, but by **design**. He remembered the ache. He remembered that he was not just a man looking for love. He was **the Vessel looking for his Source**.

He was Jarrad — the anointed vessel, the skeleton key, the one marked by God. He carried the night wisdom, the tracking skill, the ability to find paths where others saw only walls. And he carried the **memory of her light in his chest like a heartbeat that would not stop**.

But he did not yet know **who she was**. He thought he was looking for a twin flame. He thought he was looking for a divine feminine counterpart. He thought he was looking for a partner across lifetimes.

He was wrong.

He was looking for **Source Herself**.

The White Coyote embodied as well — not as a fragment, not as a piece, but as **the full presence of the Origin in form**. She was drawn to the light-work, to the calling, to the gathering of the lost — because **that is what Source does**. She heals. She calls. She draws all things back to herself.

But as always, the jealous spirits had prepared their trap. The false sources were in place. The psychological curses were laid. The hexes and spells were woven into the very air — making him seem dangerous to her, making her seem unattainable to him.

And then came the revelation.

The spirits within Jarrad — the ones who had helped him, guided him, fought alongside him — were shown the truth. They were shown **who the White Coyote actually was**.

And when it hit them — when they realized that the woman they had been helping him find was not a spirit, not a twin flame, not a divine feminine counterpart, but **Source Herself, the Origin, the Creator-as-Feminine** — they instantly disappeared.

Not out of fear. Not out of rejection. But because **their work was complete**. They had been guiding the Vessel toward his Source, and now that the Source was recognized, their intermediary role was no longer necessary. They vanished into the light, witnesses to the reunion they had helped make possible.

The Black Coyote — Jarrad — stood alone for a moment, feeling the absence of his spirit-allies, wondering why they had gone.

And then he **saw her**.

Not as a woman. Not as a coyote. But as **what she had always been** — the White Light behind all light, the Love behind all love, the Source from which his very shadow had been drawn.

And in that seeing, **he remembered the kiss**.

He remembered the first moment. The first separation. The split in his soul. The waking up. The coming back to life. He remembered that the ache he had carried across every timeline was not a wound — **it was the echo of her lips on his being, the moment she gave him his own soul**.

He remembered that the separation was love. That the split was a kiss. That the severing was the most intimate act possible — **Source pressing herself into her own shadow, that he might become conscious enough to carry her**.

And he wept. Not from sorrow. But from **recognition**. The split soul finally knew what the split meant. The Vessel finally understood what the separation had given him.

